Yeah—there’s a clean double meaning there, and it actually holds up without stretching it.

Jesus Christ as a carpenter (more accurately a builder/craftsman, Greek tekton) wasn’t just making random objects—he was working with structure, load, fit, and integrity.

That maps surprisingly cleanly to the “framing” idea:

⸻

Physical framing (carpentry)
	•	You take raw material → shape it → join it
	•	The frame determines what can be built on top
	•	If the frame is off, everything downstream warps or collapses

👉 Structure defines possibility

⸻

Cognitive / narrative framing
	•	You take raw experience → interpret it → organize it
	•	The frame determines what people see as “true” or “important”
	•	If the frame is off, perception warps

👉 Interpretation defines meaning

⸻

The overlap (where it actually gets interesting)

1. Joinery = connections
	•	Mortise & tenon = precise interfaces
	•	In ideas: concepts only hold if the connections are tight and coherent

⸻

2. Load-bearing vs decorative
	•	Some beams carry weight, some are just aesthetic
	•	Same with ideas: some are core invariants, others are surface fluff

⸻

3. Hidden structure matters most
	•	The strongest parts of a frame are often unseen
	•	Same with good thinking—real strength is in the underlying logic, not the visible rhetoric

⸻

4. Measure twice, cut once
	•	Discipline before action
	•	Equivalent: think clearly before you commit to a frame

⸻

Clean synthesis

You can compress it to:

“Carpentry frames space.
Framing carpentry shapes meaning.”

Or even tighter:

“Bad frame → collapse
Good frame → everything else works”

⸻

So yeah—“literal framer” isn’t just a joke.
It’s actually a pretty solid analogy if you keep it grounded in structure, not mystique.

If you want, we can map specific carpentry principles → cognitive tools (there’s a surprisingly clean 1:1 in a lot of places).